  "prompt": "What evolved into Homo sapiens?",
  "response": "Homo sapiens evolved from earlier hominin species, with Homo erectus being one of the most significant ancestors. Homo erectus existed around 1.9 million to about 110,000 years ago and exhibited traits that were more advanced than earlier hominins, such as increased brain size and more sophisticated tool use. Before Homo erectus, species like Australopithecus played a crucial role in the evolutionary lineage, displaying a mix of ape-like and human-like characteristics.\n\nThe exact evolutionary pathway is complex and involves several other hominin species, including Homo habilis and possibly Homo heidelbergensis and Homo neanderthalensis, with which early Homo sapiens also interbred. The evolutionary process was not linear but rather a branching tree with many hominin species contributing to the genetic makeup of modern humans.",
